Westmoreland (Sept. 4) ‚Äì All Fair Lawn Elementary schools distributed Learning To Go Bags today.

At Westmoreland, kindergarten parents stopped by the turtle statue to pick up their child‚Äôs bag that contains necessary materials to get started while learning from home. Westmoreland staffer Brianne DeLucca handed out bags to parents that contain a literacy and math folder, a Dry Erase Board and information for the first week of school.

‚ÄúHe is very excited to start school next week!‚Äù said Shuchi Khandelwal, whose son Arjun, will be starting in Mrs. Brown‚Äôs kindergarten class.

(Please Note: There are also scheduled pickups next week. Please check with your child‚Äôs principal for dates/times that apply to your school. Contents of bags vary depending on grade and materials will be added. Please await communication from your child‚Äôs teacher.)

Sept. 3 - Important Update to School Lunches Effective Sept. 8:

Recent federal and state program changes are allowing Fair Lawn Schools to continue providing free lunches to all students when school reopens on Tuesday, Sept. 8.

Pick up times at Memorial Middle School have changed. Lunches will be available for pick up between 7:30 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. every school day. More information is available on the district website under Food Service on the Students and Parents Page.

Parents can pick up their child‚Äôs lunch and multiple days‚Äô lunches may be picked up. For more information, click here: http://ow.ly/Nt2Q50BhBlq.

Student I.D. numbers are not required (as referenced in our previous Facebook post Aug. 27).

post_text: The Fair Lawn Summer Music Program wrapped up its 4-week program last week with a "Virtual Concert." The program offered students the opportunity to learn new instruments in Beginner Classes or continue their learning in Intermediate and Advanced Groups. Courses were offered in Band, Chorus, Orchestra and Jazz as well as a new Piano class. Students finished the program by recording themselves performing their music individually, and were then edited together into large ensembles.

I understand that there were some technical difficulties accessing the Kindergarten survey about reopening schools. In an effort to have the most accurate up to date information, which will help drive our decisions about reopening schools, I created a new survey, utilizing Survey Planet, instead of Google. https://s.surveyplanet.com/X_DKQ1NsD

I thank you for your patience.

Sincerely,

Nicholas J. Norcia, Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
July 16, 2020 - Fair Lawn middle and elementary schools are the 2020 recipients of the New Jersey Safe Routes to School Recognition Program for their commitment to walking and bicycling to school! Our schools reached Gold Status!

As you know, each year Fair Lawn Schools participate in Walk and Bike to School Day in the fall. This national event involves communities and schools walking and biking together and has become part of a movement for year-round safe routes to school.

Fair Lawn High School was not eligible, but participated in the walk/bike day as well.

Congratulations to all students/staff for participating and for your Gold Status achievement!!!

Community School (June 5, 2020) - After carefully looking at all the options based on the state‚Äôs guidelines and restrictions, we will be unable to run any in-person programs this summer.

Milnes (June 3, 2020) - Every night at 7 p.m. sharp, Milnes fifth-grader Arjun can be found on his front lawn giving a violin performance. You might hear him playing his favorite overture ‚ÄúOrpheus in the Underworld‚Äù or the song ‚ÄúOver the Rainbow.‚Äù Music For A Cause is Arjun‚Äôs initiative that began on Memorial Day to raise money for Fair Lawn first responders.

To date, he has raised $88 and according to his mother, and he hopes to raise more than $200 with additional donations, plus his parents‚Äô matching funds.

Signs posted all over Fair Lawn supporting first responders inspired Arjun to do his part, but after the tragic events in Minneapolis, he focused his attention on Fair Lawn police because ‚Äúhe understands that the wrong action of one cop shouldn‚Äôt mean he should stop loving his Fair Lawn Police Department.‚Äù All of the proceeds will be donated to the FLPD.

Stop by Terhune Place (we received permission from his parents to post the street) to support Arjun‚Äôs mission. His fundraiser is planned until this weekend.

June 3, 2020 - Radburn fifth-grader Ezra Fineman was recently asked to speak on a virtual panel for a national sales meeting of a pharmaceutical company. Ezra shared his experiences living in isolation due to a serious medical condition when he was young and gave ideas for what families currently sheltering in place due to COVID-19 can do for fun while at home. The panel was joined by a surprise guest astronaut and Capt. Jim Lovell from the Apollo 13 mission!

Capt. Lovell shared stories about his missions to the moon and inspired everyone with his message to stay optimistic in the face of adversity. Ezra has been fascinated by space exploration and rockets since he was two years old, so he was thrilled to get the chance to interact with ex-NASA astronaut!

Westmoreland (May 5, 2020) - Westmoreland students have been loving our schoolwide Flat Teacher Project!

If you have ever read the story, ‚ÄúFlat Stanley,‚Äù I am sure you can understand the joy students felt when they received a flattened version of their teachers in the mail! Students were charged with the task of taking their teacher on an adventure each day....and boy have they been busy!

Teachers have accompanied students on their first bike ride without training wheels, enjoyed coffee in bed in the Barbie Dream House, observed the night sky through a telescope and have driven bulldozers through yards to help with the yard work.

This project has warmed the hearts of both students and staff as they exchange emails and pictures to learn about each adventure!

If you have ever read the story, ‚ÄúFlat Stanley,‚Äù I am sure you can understand the joy students felt when they received a flattened version of their teachers in the mail! Students were charged with the task of taking their teacher on an adventure each day....and boy have they been busy!

Teachers have accompanied students on their first bike ride without training wheels, enjoyed coffee in bed in the Barbie Dream House, observed the night sky through a telescope and have driven bulldozers through yards to help with the yard work.

This project has warmed the hearts of both students and staff as they exchange emails and pictures to learn about each adventure!

post_text: Radburn (April 25) - A gallery of photos from Radburn School's Flex Fridays, which began on April 24. The district implemented Flex Fridays to give students an assortment of mindful activities that focus on self-awareness, self-management, social awareness, responsible decision-making and relationship skills, which is tied to the district's social emotional learning standards. Take a look at what the kids chose: everything from yoga, to reading to younger students, to building a fort with their family.

post_text:
Fair Lawn Public Schools continues to support health care workers by making another donation.

Mike Shansky, Community School Director, donated 30 cases of aftercare snacks to Hackensack University Medical Center (HUMC) on April 9. To minimize contact, Superintendent Nick Norcia delivered the boxes to the home of a HUMC nurse, who graciously agreed to bring with her to work and pass out to staff.

‚ÄúWe are so appreciative of our medical community, who continue to show bravery, courage and selflessness,‚Äù said Superintendent Norcia. ‚ÄúWe hope our small gesture makes a difference for the true heroes on the front lines.‚Äù

Important message from the Superintendent, Nicholas J. Norcia

Good Evening Fair Lawn Community,

I am writing to you tonight to remind everyone that beginning tomorrow our Spring Break will begin. The last few weeks, we as a community, have been moving at a speed that words can‚Äôt even describe and over the next week, please take time to rest, rejuvenate, spend time with your family, and most importantly stay healthy!

When we return on April 13th, Week 4 of Fair Lawn‚Äôs Distance Learning Plan will pick up where we left off. Also, Governor Murphy is expected to announce additional information on or around April 17th about the status of all schools in New Jersey. Once we have more information, we will be sharing that information as soon as possible.

Finally, should we make any changes to Fair Lawn‚Äôs Distance Learning Plan Week 4, we will communicate that with you accordingly.

Thank you, stay healthy Fair Lawn and enjoy your break!

Sincerely,

Nicholas J. Norcia, Superintendent of Schools

TODAY, APRIL 1, 2020, IS US CENSUS DAY

IMPORTANT MESSAGE FROM THE U.S. CENSUS:

The time is now. Help shape your future, and your community's future, by responding to the 2020 Census.

Most households received their invitation to respond to the 2020 Census between March 12 ‚Äì 20. These official Census Bureau mailings (http://ow.ly/k0uq50z03hq) will include detailed information and a Census ID for completing the Census online.

In addition to an invitation to respond, some households will receive a paper questionnaire (sometimes known as the census form). You do not need to wait for your paper questionnaire to respond to the Census. Please complete your census form online, by phone, or by mail when your invitation to respond arrives.

Please help us by filling our your census form at http://ow.ly/LZbf50z03hn or go to mycensus2020.gov.

MMS (March 27) - In a week filled with many firsts, uncertainty and hope, we wanted to share with you Raunak Singh's timely article on COVID-19 in "Time For Kids," a print and digital magazine tailored for young people. Raunak, a sixth-grader at MMS, is a reporter for the media outlet and shares his perspective on the pandemic. One of Raunak's insights: "So try to be kind in your community. If we work together, maintain safe practices, and keep ourselves busy at home, we can fight this little microbe!"
http://ow.ly/FPcI50yYau7
shared_text:
TIMEFORKIDS.COM
Kids Report on COVID-19: Raunak in New Jersey
text:
MMS (March 27) - In a week filled with many firsts, uncertainty and hope, we wanted to share with you Raunak Singh's timely article on COVID-19 in "Time For Kids," a print and digital magazine tailored for young people. Raunak, a sixth-grader at MMS, is a reporter for the media outlet and shares his perspective on the pandemic. One of Raunak's insights: "So try to be kind in your community. If we work together, maintain safe practices, and keep ourselves busy at home, we can fight this little microbe!"
http://ow.ly/FPcI50yYau7

March 26, 2020 ‚Äì The Fair Lawn School District donated 13-thousand gloves and around 400 face masks to Valley Hospital in Ridgewood, Bergen New Bridge Medical Center in Paramus, and to Fair Lawn first responders after area hospitals put out a call for personal protection equipment, running short because of the coronavirus pandemic.

‚ÄúOur principals, nurses and science teachers quickly went to work and gathered whatever we had in stock in our schools, labs and in the nurses‚Äô offices,‚Äù said Superintendent Nick Norcia. ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre in this together, and the only way we‚Äôre going to get out of it is together. As I always say, it takes a village.‚Äù

‚ÄúOn behalf of the Fair Lawn School District, we thank our medical personnel, our Fair Lawn first responders who are working tirelessly transporting patients to our hospitals, and everyone in the medical community for their dedication and service treating this virus.‚Äù

FLHS (March 24, 2020) ‚Äì FLHS students participated in the March 1 M3 MathWorks Math Challenge sponsored by the Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics. Students worked for 14 hours to write a paper on a real world challenge. This year's challenge was about the turnover from diesel fuel to electricity for long haul trucking. Students had to create a paper that would discuss the effect on infrastructure, economics and the environment.

The organization evaluates the papers using strict criteria. The FLHS team finished in the top 4 percent of ll papers submitted nationwide. They have received Honorable Mention and $1000 to share for college expenses.

‚ÄúWe have been participating in this challenge for about 10 years. We have had two other teams place very high in the past,‚Äù said Karen Rood, teacher of mathematics and computer science. ‚ÄúThe team‚Äôs finished paper is very professional and they should be very proud of their work.‚Äù

Please congratulate the FLHS team:
‚Ä¢ Angela Zhang
‚Ä¢ Jordan Mach
‚Ä¢ Zain Kamal
‚Ä¢ Tavorr Vaxman-Magid
‚Ä¢ Elaine Steinberg

post_text:
Milnes (March 5) ‚Äì Milnes held its annual VIP Reading Day, one of the many activities of the week to celebrate Read Across America. Guest readers - Fair Lawn Board of Education trustees, administrators from Fair Lawn Schools, former teachers, Fair Lawn Mayor Peluso (a graduate of Milnes!), Special 3 Officer Sean Talt, and many others - look forward to this event each year where they select their favorite book to read to a classroom.

Some of the selections were ‚ÄúOne the Night You Were Born,‚Äù to ‚ÄúThe Sneetches and Other Stories,‚Äù and ‚ÄúGiraffe Problems.‚Äù

Throughout the week at Milnes, students and staff celebrated a reading activity: Monday was Wear A Shirt You Can Read Day; on Tuesday, author Michael Dooling visited; Wednesday was Storybook Day; Thursday was VIP Reading Day; and Friday will be Buddy Reading.

A big thank you to the PTA for organizing and volunteering at the weeklong Scholastic Book Fair and to the fourth and fifth-grade escorts who accompanied the VIPs to their classrooms.

Special thank you to the H.B. Milnes Read Across America Committee for organizing!!!
